-- Accor, Areva, Gecina, PPR, RTL Group : Europe Equity Preview
-- B y   K s e n i a   G a l o u c h k o
-- 2012-01-18T05:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-18/accor-areva-gecina-ppr-rtl-group-europe-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European (SXXP)  (SXXP) trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The  Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 0.9 percent to 253.27. The
 Stoxx 50 Index  gained 0.8 percent to 2,436.46. The  Euro Stoxx 50
Index , a benchmark measure for nations using the euro, gained
1.5 percent to 2,396.63.  Accor SA (AC)  : Europe’s biggest hotel company said sales
rose 2.5 percent in 2011 and confirmed its profit forecast,
helped by growth in economy lodgings. Accor fell 0.3 percent to
21.08 euros.  Areva SA (AREVA)  (AREVA FP): The world’s largest producer of
nuclear equipment commissioned an energy storage system based on
hydrogen for a utility-scale photovoltaic plant on the French
Mediterranean island of  Corsica . Areva retreated 1.4 percent to
19.67 euros.  BASF SE (BAS)  (BAS GY): The Ludwigshafen, Germany-based company’s
decision to move its plant-science division to the U.S. from
 Germany  because of resistance to genetically modified crops is
“devastating” for European agriculture, a German farm lobby,
Deutscher Raiffeisenverband e.V., said. BASF gained 1.5 percent
to 58.79 euros.  Gecina SA (GFC)  : Paris’s largest office landlord said
it’s close to completing the 500 million-euro ($637 million)
asset-sale program announced in October by Chief Executive
Officer Bernard Michel. Gecina declined 0.8 percent to 64.37
euros.  PPR SA (PP)  : The French owner of the Gucci luxury brand
is considering selling Redcats’ Avenue clothing business in the
U.S. as part of a bankruptcy filing for the brand, according to
a person with knowledge of the plan. PPR dropped 0.8 percent to
116.05 euros.  RTL Group SA (RTL)  : The television company owned by
Bertelsmann AG bought the German coupon portal Gutscheine.de,
Handelsblatt reported, citing the group’s Interactive GmbH head
Marc Schroeder. RTL declined 1 percent to 72.46 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
